caption:
This fine body of inspirational people, dug deep around a successful 30 mile yomp today. We as a team could not be more proud, or grateful to have accompanied them on their own personal journey across Dartmoor. We would also like to give a big thank you and a special mention to Diane Warwick who persisted on doing her own 30 miler (31) at home after picking up a niggling injury not so long ago. In general, a huge thank you to everybody involved, tonight brings a well deserved rest .

caption:
Found these floating in the waves today at the beach.
And if you look really closely at my hand, you can see the sparkly residue of the plastic wrapper.
Delightful.
**
Is this really what you want your kids to swim in?
Is this what you want the ocean animals to be surrounded by? Or accidentally consume?
Is convenience so important that you can't say no to that plastic encased water or juice or soda?
**
Planning ahead is easy.
A small cooler filled with ice packs and reusable water bottles.
Snacks in reusable containers.
BASIC.
Convenience is what has gotten us into this mess.
And the mess is not going to go away until we start re-evaluating our needs for convenience and weigh it against how much we care about a livable future for our kids.

caption:
"The highlight for me was the look on every single persons face when they looked in the back of that lorry and saw just how many pots had been collected. I was able to see, again and again, everyone suddenly feel that same pride I had been feeling all weekend. It was magical and totally inspring" 😍.
.
This weekend, 4-5th May 2019, Trevisker Garden Centre Beach Guardian and The Ocean Recovery Project hosted 'The Great Pot Amnesty' at @trevisker_garden_centre ♻️.
.
Over the weekend, we have been encouraging the people of Cornwall (and even further afield), to get out into their garden sheds, dust off those cobwebs and pull out their old plastic gardening pots and seed trays. We were asking for these to be brought up to the Garden Centre, where we were collecting them in 'Lola - the Lovely Orange Lorry' 🌳🌱🧡.
.
Tomorrow morning, Lola is going to be collected by The Ocean Recovery Project. .
All of the pots and seed trays that were collected will be recycled.
.
You cannot recycle these plastics kerbside.
.
This weekend has made a huge impact on all involved. None of us expected to finish today with an overflowing container old and unwanted plastic pots, many having travelled so many miles to get to us.
.
Thank you, and well done to everyone that was involved.
.
To find out more what will happen to these pots, check out The @oceanrecoveryproject and @odysseyinnovation.
.
#iamabeachguardian

caption:
My 2 year old leading the way and showing us all what we should be doing!

I am so proud to see how educated my little boy is already at the age of 2 - he will tell you that he goes to the beach to clean up the rubbish to save the whales and sharks; he can determine what the rubbish is and how it shouldn't be at the beach ... how does he know all of this? Because I have shown him because I am a parent and that is my responsibility.

Seeing how Kavai understands all of this has made me even more passionate to educate our generation as there really is no excuse - if a 2 year knows what belongs on the beach and what doesn't then all of us can educate our children to.

We all live on this planet and many of us take it for granted but the time has come when all of us should be grateful that we get to call this incredible planet our home!! #bethechange #ocean #ocean

caption: In about 2 months I'll be moving from Barcelona to a town in The Netherlands that's not close to the sea, so I won't be able to continue my beach clean-ups on a regular basis. This means that while we still live here I'll be doing a lot of beach cleanups. I set a goal to do Cleanups on 7 different beaches in the area over the next few weeks. I started yesterday at Sitges beach. In the 2,5 hours on the beach I filled up one big shopping bag and 6 smaller buckets and after that there was still a lot of trash left on the beach, but I had to leave. It sometimes really frustrates me that I'm never able to fully clean a beach and that I always have to leave trash behind on the beach..

caption: The first image is the trash we picked up on the beach in Florida. For little over an hour we did a beach clean up. I wouldn't have felt right enjoying the beach without doing that. We as humans want to enjoy the beauty of it all and that is fine. But our actions cause trauma to the animals in the ocean. I just want to urge you ALL to do the right thing. Grab a bag and pick up some of this trash while you are out enjoying a beach day. It doesn't take much honestly, just your time. It pains me to see what the animals have to go through because of us. We can make the ocean healthy again. It starts with us. You may not like the videos I have posted but this is reality. We should be more mindful of our actions. Clean up the beaches. We can change things one garbage bag at a time. Just start! The poor turtle! 😩💙 #marineconservation #ocean #savetheocean #wildlife #animals #beachcleanup #animalconservation #ecosystem #fish #shark #seaturtle #savethereef

caption:
No plastic here! Every trip to the beach there seems to be a plastic beach toy left on the sand from someone who had been there previously. I totally get how this happens and we may have done the same in the past. We have had plastic buckets and spades before and they break so easily that new ones are purchased every summer.
.

For a while now, we have bought items that have multi uses that the kids can take to the beach also. Mia has some garden equipment like digging tools made of wood and metal and a tin watering can. Today we took these ikea kids metal kitchen tools, these are great for the bath too! My mum is buying some @plantoysuk flower pots for Romans birthday as they can be used in so many ways including beach, bath, play dough, mud.
. 
If we were to leave any of these items on the beach 😲 which I really hope doesn't happen, then at least they won't break down into micro plastics and go straight into the sea.
.

2 minute beach clean completed today by Mia 💚

I’ve always struggled with winters, perhaps because growing up in Sweden it was almost winter all the time and I feel like my body and soul craves sunshine ☀️ and warmth, I’ve been escaping winter for many years but this winter I decided to stay with the darkness and cold and go deep into meditation with nature and the process of letting go and “die” to be born fresh and new again. Very interesting to stay with this process. But omg I can help myself from dreaming of beachdays like these 🌸

Awesome turnout and effort this morning at the NOTL beach clean up, put on by @agreenerfuture and @paddleniagara.  Together along with 50+ others we were able to collect 4228 pieces of litter (styrofoam, single use plastic bottles, tires, microplastics, etc.). Check out @agreenerfuture if you'd like to support them or get out to one of their events around Lake Ontario. .
.
 Even if you don't make it out to clean up event, you can still make a big impact by learning about the products you use on a daily basis, supporting local businesses that have greener options, refusing SINGLE USE plastic items such as .
.
-plastic grocery bags
-coffee cups
-plastic straws and cutlery
-plastic water bottles .
.

caption: Let Carl sleep in this morning. So after getting my espresso at Pipes, I headed to Beacons Beach and did beach clean up. I intended to do just the Beacons area, but the tide was reasonably low and the weather was in my favor..... so I scoured the beach from the north edge of Beacons to the stairs of Stonesteps. Fortunately it wasn’t too bad this morning as it was mainly smalls like bits of styrofoam and plastic water bottle caps. The most interesting thing was the little sail jelly things that washed up in various stages of loosing their blue gummy parts. If you didn’t know what they were, you would assume they were bits of plastic washing up. Nope. I remember when I went on a trip up the CA coast when I was about 20 and saw beaches with hundreds of these guys washed up. On my way back to the car at Beacons, I happened upon two sweet frames someone had put on the curb. Yoink!!!! More frames to use for my art show pieces! Nice! Anyway, time to get back to work! #beachcleanup #beaconsbeachcleanup #stonestepsbeach #beachcleanupis247365 #trashpinchers #washedupsealife #encinitasbeachcleanup #leucadianative

caption:
Questo fine settimana a Biarritz ho imparato tanto. Ho fatto surf per la prima volta, ho festeggiato il mio compleanno partecipando alla pulizia di una spiaggia che affaccia sull’Atlantico, ho celebrato senza i miei affetti ma assieme a belle persone conosciute solo il giorno precedente.
Persone con ideali, sogni, valori simili ai miei, motivate, pronte ad agire e sporcarsi le mani per raggiungere i propri obiettivi. Che poi, pensandoci, dovrebbero essere gli obiettivi di tutti, perché tutti vogliamo un mondo migliore e sognamo un futuro più pulito per noi e per chi domani vivrà su questo incredibile e pazzesco pianeta. 
Grazie a chi ha condiviso questa esperienza con me e a chi ha partecipato a distanza, mandandomi sostegno e affetto, come solo voi sapete fare 💙 #cheerstotheocean

caption:
ONE TON 〰️
Can you believe yesterday we, @5minutecostarica recovered almost ONE TON of marine debris in less than two hours? 
Well, yes. .
.
HEROES AND SPONSORS
〰️
We went with a group of 45 volunteers coming from a corporation with the collaboration of @cervezaimperialcr. .
.
.
CIRCULAR ECONOMY 〰️
We left our comfy bed at 5 am to go and clean the beach and we returned at 7 pm with all sorted and ready to recycle this into Eco blocks.  Our organization made a commitment few months ago to RECYCLE 100% of all of the material recovered in our cleanups. .
.
CAMPAIGN 〰️
This huge quantity and such a short span of time raised many questions about what is needed to save our oceans SO we came back thinking about a campaign we will throw out there pretty soon. 〰️🌊〰️
.
FOLLOW OUR MOVEMENT AND SUBSCRIBE TO CHANGE.
www.5minutebeachcleanup.com

caption: We had an absolutely FANTASTIC #beachcleanup yesterday! Over 100 people attended and over 60 bags of trash collected. I’m really glad I could collaborate with #cleanc #gregplayer to make a huge success out of it. People were absolutely shocked at the amount of tiny trash pieces that had washed in from the ocean and didn’t realise until I showed them. I’m glad I could help educate a lot of our younger generation to take their future into their hands and in turn educate their friends. We had #metropolicecadets join us and multiple school groups from as far as Somerset west, brackenfell and fairmont. Multiple church groups joined and outdoor adventure clubs too! A few volunteers from Table View Neighborhood Watch also joined. THANK YOU!!! Elapsed time: 2 hours | location: #bloubergstrand #kitebeach | most collected item : small pieces of plastic (sweetie wrappers) #saveouroceans #plasticfreeoceans #tvnw

caption:
After China, Indonesia is the world's second largest cause of plastic waste floating in the oceans. 50% of the trash doesn't get to landfill. Every individual in every country can make a difference. Be the change you want to see in the world. The woman standing next to me is Emma who founded the organisation "ocean mimic" to clean oceans and beaches by walking and diving weekly. Today we collected 49 kg of trash in Canggu, Bali.

.
.

caption:
Yin and Yang...
.
Seeing the good and the bad today after receiving some photos of my daughter @hannahcar and her friends, who were cleaning up their local beach after a heavy swell brought loads of rubbish ashore.
.
They filled 15 bags and a bucket, but there was still loads left. While collecting all the rubbish, they found a hermit crab using a syringe cap instead of a shell (see second to last photo). Heartbreaking 💔. Us humans have so much to answer for...
.
.
.

caption:
去海邊來回大概80公里。

有段時間滿排斥騎長途的，
因為怕車壞掉，大概是剛出來工作，
修完車戶頭剩幾百塊嚇到，
（結果那段時間都在公司蹭便當哈）

現在覺得，騎遠一點，
能夠淨灘走灘吹海風聽海聲，
換來平靜的心靈，
豐富的視野也挺好的，
興趣使然的淨灘得到的自我滿足！

總之學習跟自己協商，
選擇會相對多一些，
世界也會豐富許多，
也不會覺得自己被改變，
而是有所選擇，
隨自己意思改變目的而已。

對了，最近新購入的支架TAKEWAY，
認真好用，雖然我沒接業配，
之後就請小綠多幫忙了👍👍
#sea #taiwan #taichung #beachcleanup

caption:
Morning beach run turned into a beach clean up; change your routine and get clean dudes!!! I was overwhelmed with how much trash I saw while running that I stopped and started collecting it.
It’s not a difficult task to pick up your own trash! Plastic packaging and toys take years to break down and sadly it’s frequently consumed by wild life! Take two seconds, pick up your garbage and you could save that cute dolphin you see happily swimming by!🐬 Here’s a few pics of a few things I picked up (obviously didn’t take pictures of all of it) These super common items can easily be taken home with you OR thrown in the garbage/ recycling!
Take care of our oceans 🦀🌊🐬
#saveouroceans #beachcleanup #protectthemarinelife

caption:
"Preserving our Planet and it's People, to Protect our Purpose", is one of the major Causes Decathlon as a whole is fighting for today. 
Decathlon Ghana in our bid to make sports accessible to all, continued with our monthly Beach Cleanup Exercise at the Coco Beach in Nungua last Saturday 27th April 2019. As always we collaborated with *Plastic Punch*, a private NGO, we have partnered with for our environmental and sanitation projects, and whose vision is aligned with Decathlon Ghana's vision of preserving the environment.
Indeed it was a fun filled event as we collectively *PUNCHED THE PLASTICS* off the beach, *EDUCATED* the community on the importance of keeping our Beaches clean, and of course, *PRACTISED SEVERAL SPORTS* together on the clean Beach.
We entreat all like minded organisations and groups to join us on the last Saturday of every month for this worthy cause. 
Below are some images.
Thanks to Decathlon Ghana our USERS through SPORTS will have more PLEASURE, better HEALTH and a better SOCIAL INTEGRATION thus LIVE LIFE to the FULLEST.

OUR KPI: Increase life expectancy at birth from 67 to 77 years.

#Like and #Share to support the movement.

.
I got to spend the morning alongside this diverse powerhouse of a woman during the New Moon rocky shore beach cleanup in Muizenberg.
.
Do yourself a favor, no more excuses, give them a follow and get involved - a hands-on approach to making a difference if there ever was one. We need to keep our oceans clean, so make sure you take home any rubbish from trips to the beach!

caption:
"Mum, I can't look mad for too long!" she said when I took a photo of Cecilia at the end of our #beachcleanup at @alohasurf.nl today.
That is because she is a nice human being. And because she wants good for everyone, including animals and plants, the beach she loves to play at and the sea that splashes up against the shore.
But when you empty a bag full of trash, including tiny threads of plastic that look like sea weed, soda cans, styrofoam chunks, cigarette stubs, plastic wrappings and spiky plastic forks ... just after 45 minutes of weeding through the dunes and the sand ... well, then you will feel mad the least. Mad about the people who didn't care to find a proper bin for their waste.
But also you will feel guilty and ashamed for consuming and producing so much trash yourself. For continuing to do so day after day because it is convenient. Because it is how our world is programmed today.
So right now, I am sitting with this mix of feelings. Looking at my daughter who is proud of having done good today. Knowing that there is a long way ahead of us. And so little time.
.
.
.
#nofilter #beachcleanup #whatthetrash #thereisnoplanetb  #scheveningenbeach #alohasurf #cleanyourshitup

caption:
Every "coin" has two sides, a positive & a negative, which side will you choose today??
Repost from @oceanic.elizabeth Yesterday was INCREDIBLE! We were 150,000 people asking for climate action in Montreal! It was the biggest march that took place! Over 1,4 million young people in 125 countries skipped school, inspired by Greta Thunberg, to demand stronger climate policies in what may be one of the largest environmental protest in history. From Australia and New Zealand, to Asia, Europe, Africa, North America and South America, students from all over the world took the streets to demand change now.‬ "Biggest day of global climate action ever”says 350.org
🌎
‪"This movement had to happen, we didn't have a choice" ‬"I don't want you to be hopeful, I want you to panic. I want you to feel the fear I feel every day. And I want you to act." - said the Swedish activist, 16 years old, and strike leader @gretathunberg
🌎
Many students expressed anger, fear and disappointment that adults have not acted. Many also expressed hope for a green economy at the United Nations believe is necessary to forestall catastrophic climate change.
🌎
We need to do way more, as individual, to put more pression. You vote every time you buy something, you vote every time you eat something, you vote every time you do something. Please choose wisely. And please join the next march, we need everybody to be apart of the movement, actions speak louder than words.  And this is not even the beginning. Because we have done our homework✊🏽
📷 @victoriafigueroa14
.
. via @rhinogirl18 .

caption:
⠀⠀⠀
【浪人祭 Vagabond Festival －北海淨灘｜活動倒數20天！】
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
大家好 我是浪人祭主辦人🙋🏻‍♂️
活動已經進入倒數20天❗️
我們的思緒和其他音樂祭的主辦單位一樣，陷入倒數的焦慮輪迴與焦躁的情緒中，面對舉辦一場環保＋音樂祭還有許多許多藝術的活動，沙灘上辦音樂節費用更是難以負荷，很多的資源得來不易、很多的人手難尋，很常時候我都覺得這是在積欠人情。
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
『環保這條路真的不好走』
蒐集而來的環保裝飾物用於呈現各種畫面，浪人祭製作任何東西的困難度都是以倍數成長。
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
說白了『最輕鬆的方式往往是最不環保的』
堅持理想需要準備大量的資金投入運轉這個活動，眼看目前的票房與金流狀況，我當然也很擔心辦完浪人祭之後是不是就在街巷裡成為真正的【浪人】了。
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
跟大家一樣每日每夜平均睡8個小時
每一天的工作時間差不多也就是扣掉睡眠的16小時左右。
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
工作時間我都在幹嘛呢？
早上10點後，我幾乎都在公館工作室
與夥伴們討論工作、分配所有事項
遇到夥伴們全都期中考的上禮拜，我一個人在工作室像是棵木頭一樣的進行著許多待辦事項
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
有時候跑到福隆，浪人祭活動會場場勘
有時候跑去北海岸撿浮球
有時候跑到內湖回收站轉開過期氣泡水蒐集寶特瓶
有時候跑到泰山裝置藝術工作室做道具
凌晨3點是習慣離開工作室的時間
再晚一點的回家路上，是卡在其他人準備上班的車陣中
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
但我知道，就算再難、再忙
，在遠處還有許多等待這場活動發生的樂迷及愛環保的朋友
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
我們會繼續站在這裡把這場活動呈現到最好⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
無論到最後一刻票房狀況如何，面對了多大的壓力
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
就盡情的笑吧！
笑那些還沒買票的人，讓他們知道這場活動多好玩
真正去做些能改變土地的事吧！無論什麼樣的形式
跨出去都行，你可以開心快樂的聽音樂，也可以滿懷感念土地的心來做環保。
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
無論你買票與否，我們在這裡等你。
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

caption:
Die erste Woche ist geschafft 💪🏻
Hier auf #Bali unterstütze ich momentan ein #Volunteer Programm und bringe Kinder englisch bei und reinige die Strände in unserem Dorf.  Es ist wirklich einiges zutun und vorallem das Beach cleaning scheint eine Syphilis Arbeit zu sein, denn am nächsten Tag ist der #Strand wieder mit Müll bedeckt. Aber ich weiß, dass jede Zahnbürste, jede Windel und jeder Strohhalm den er aufsammeln ein Schritt in die richtige Richtung ist. Dieses Wochenende waren wir in #Uluwatu und haben am Strand unter der Sonne geschlafen, haben viele Healthy Bowls gegessen und wunderschöne #Tempel gesehen. 
Einfach mal durchatmen und die Zeit genießen 💕🌸

text: Wie schön💕🙌🙌🙌. Ich möchte auch sehr gerne am Volunteer Programm teilnehmen, mir gefällt das Konzept so unglaublich gut🙌🏻. Generell anderen Menschen zu helfen und der Natur etwas gutes zutun, ist heutzutage so wichtig ❤️
@cba_15 finde ich auch und zudem bekommt noch so viele neue Freunde Bzw eine komplett neue Familie und die Erlebnisse 🥰 ich verbringe hier gerade eine der schönsten Zeiten meines Lebens

Ich glaube man lernt sich dadurch nochmal auf eine ganz neue Seite kennen und bekommt auf vieles eine ganz neue Sicht. Und man darf an unglaublichen Momenten teilnehmen, die man bestimmt nie vergessen wird💕 Ich wünsch dir auf jeden Fall eine sehr schöne Zeit ❤️☀️
@cba_15 da hast du recht, danke dir 💕🌸 ich hoffe du findest auch ein ganz tolles Projekt welches dir viel Spaß bereiten wird ❤️✨

Back on insta after a few months break that was so needed. This styrofoam buoy inspired me to share my LOVE for this EARTH again in hopes of reaching people with a message that what you do matters - any changes you make to be more loving to our planet helps! Let’s change and demand change... like no more styrofoam buoys or containers. Bring your own container. Keep some in your car or in your bag. Easy to do! 💚
p.s. yes that’s a sneaky finger - not aimed at the gorgeous oceanside as it appears - but aimed at the destructive materials in my hand. When we choose disposable products, we are in essence giving nature the finger. So be kind to the environment and find an earth friendly alternative... promise there is one for almost everything! 💙

caption:
PINK PLASTIC BEACH🏝
⠀
⠀⠀Every year situation becomes worse. Not only Bali, but whole Indonesia becoming real “plastic paradise”.
⠀
⠀⠀A travelling couple Marie Fe and Jake Snow has shared these photos they made in exactly the same spot, but 12 months apart from each other. It’s Indonesia's famous Pink Beach in the Komodo National Park. In 2018 it was quite clean, but now beach covered by plastic rubbish: bottles, boxes and cups.
⠀
“If we don’t act now, this will become a normality. Our beaches, our oceans and our world will be covered in plastic,” – said guys in their Instagram.
⠀
⠀⠀If you try to find photos from this place in other accounts you’ll see very beautiful pictures. Every travel-blogger wants to have beautiful photos in his blog, that’s why many Instagram influencers use Photoshop. But in real life we can’t clean beaches and save turtles and fishes by Photoshop. This will simply serve to hide the true extent of the issue. ⠀
⠀⠀
♻️🌎 That’s why project #BecauseWeLiveHere talking about real measures.
First of all it’s Local station for plastic waste recycling, and river autonomous filtration system. ⠀
⠀⠀What do you think about these initiatives?
⠀
Photo by @mariefeandjakesnow
⠀

caption:
Yesterday my daughter and I did our usual beach walk; she was armed with her bucket and spade to build castles, I was armed with a bag to pick up any rubbish we might encounter at the beach. -
There had been a storm the night before and the storm water had run off from the streets to the beach. I was devastated to realise that my small bag was never going to be big enough to fit all of the rubbish that had been flushed down to the sand.
-
Feeling helpless, I filled my bag and left the rest behind. It was a feeling of utter frustration; whatever I could do would never be enough to make a difference. -
I haven’t been able to stop thinking about this sight at the beach. I’ve been reading and finding ways to do more, thinking how my small actions could perhaps become something more significant.
-
I am not pretending to be perfect, but the least I can do is to send out this little message to all of you out there - and hope that perhaps we can do something bigger together.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
#nordicminimalism #minimalisthome #mykonmari #konmari #simpleliving #mynordichome #boligpluss #bolig #bolig #skandinaviskahem #simplicity #nordiskahem #joycheck #howyouhome #mindfullliving #lessismore #lookafterourplanet #takecareoftheocean #cleanupchallenge #beachcleanup

text: Love your feed! Dm us for a Marine Life accessory!

Yes... it can be sometimes so decouraging to see things like that and it makes sad and helpless.. but we have to make our little efforts every day and teach our children to be more thoughtful about our environment.
I understand your frustration but remember you still did something instead of passing by and ignoring the trash on the beach.
@anureinson That is so true. It’s still better to do something, than not do anything 😕 Such a valuable lesson to my daughter! She was so saddened to see the rubbish on a usually pretty clean beach 🙁
@villyjk Well that is very true. Thank you for your encouragement 💛
Good on you Maria ❤️ every bit counts and you did more than most. X
It's so sad, and so easy to close our eyes on these things in our hectic everyday life! 😔 Thank you for remind me to try more 💛
You're doing a great job hun ❤️
@thedesignchaser I realise it’s the little things that we can all do to help, but it frustrates me that I can’t do more 😕 💛
@jnnikas That is so true - and I think that’s the case with most of us. We are caught up in our daily lives, too busy to notice. But when you do, it’s all you see 😕
You are so good for doing that. I hate it when people just leave their trash!
@melissaselmin 💛 I feel like we’re doing enough damage with everything else, the least we can do is not litter!
Oh dear! This really is devastating 😔
What a wonderful thing to do - and something we should all do. Together we can make a difference

I feel your pain. It is the same here in Belgium. The more litter we collect on the streets/forest nearby, the more there seems to be scattered around a few days later... is really frustrating. But I still believe this is the way to go. Doing the small things you can even if they seem to be tiny steps against the crowd... 💚 halaus, rakas Maria!

@eszterbedy I love this (and many other things) about Japan: people there have this “collective” sense for these things, you hardly ever see any rubbish around. Here, some seem to think “well, I’m not picking it up, I didn’t throw it there in the first place” 😕 it scares me to think where we’ll end up if nothing is done about the amount of plastic and other waste (disposable coffee cups, plastic straws!) 😔

caption: Even though we live in one of Australia’s more remote locations, the Torres Strait Islands, it doesn’t make us immune to the impacts of large scale consumerism. We visit this part of our island at the very least once a fortnight and are more shocked every visit with the scale of marine debris deposits. From thongs, toothbrushes, lighters and oil drums to children’s toys, berthing hawsers, water and detergent bottles and indistinguishable micro plastics - we’ve seen it all. Much of the debris can be traced to international trawling vessels and relatively close neighbouring countries - having said that, much comes from closer to home. It’s hard to keep caring when it seems so largely out of our hands but after all, in the end, our actions do all count and we’ll keep doing our part by lessening our consumer footprints, closing the loop and educating awareness 🌴 #marinedebris #reducereuserecycle #closetheloop #beachcleanup #consumerism #hornisland #torresstrait #plasticpollution #stopthesource

caption:
A bit of early morning beach combing along the Lang Lang foreshore.
I got to Lang Lang beach at sunrise and spent a couple of hours combing through the foreshore, fishing area, car park and over 1km of beach and dune area.
I have recovered some 30+ kg of rubbish, at a guess. I don’t expect I got it all, but I got everything last I saw; including hundreds of metres of fishing line, hooks, lures, jigs etc. 
If you see rubbish at the beach, please pick it up. #everypiecehelps #vicbeachclean #vicbeachcleanup #beachcleaning #beachcleanup #cleanbeach #cleanbeaches #beachclean #keepaustraliabeautiful #cleanupaustralia #pickupyourtrash #beachtrash #beachgarbage #saveouroceans #nolittering #plasticfreeforthesea #dontlitter #marineconservation #seashepherd

Alguien más se la pasa levantando basura ajena cuando está paseando? No puedo evitarlo 🙈
.
Podemos disfrutar de la naturaleza 🌴🌊☀️sin dejar rastro. El planeta es nuestra casa 🌎 .
Por eso si vemos basura en el camino, levantémosla🤙🏼. No nos cuesta nada y le podemos salvar la vida a un animalito, reduciendo además la contaminación de ese espacio natural 💪🏼💚
.
Etiqueté varias cuentas referentes sobre el tema para quienes quieran chusmear 🌊 😊
.
_______________
.
Someone else picking the rubbish while taking a walk? I can’t stop 🙈
.
We can enjoy nature 🌴🌊☀️ without leaving a trace. The planet is our home 🌎
.
So if we see trash on the road, let's pick it up🤙🏼. It costs us nothing and we can save the life of an animal, also reducing pollution 💪🏼💚
.
.

caption:
Today’s National Beach Clean-Up Week💚
.
.
This week has been Norway’s national beach clean-up week, and today was the national beach clean-up day🏝 It’s been amazing to see all the engagement happening throughout this week! But... I would therefore also remind us all that any action towards a better world is not only to be done for one specific day. Not to say that we should all go pick up trash for hours each day (although if you can, sure do🤩). However, it doesn’t need to be Earth Day or Becah Clean-Up Day in order for us to take action. Today could be any day, and we’d still have that same power to make change. So, regardless of the day, let’s make a change every day - small or big... because picking up that one piece of trash could avoid a potential death of an animal. We can fix this - piece by piece, and choice by choice as we reduce our personal use of packaging and plastic💚
.
.
Thank you everyone who helped out today and throughout the week! We don’t have a picture of everyone, so this is just a few of al the people who joined this week💚 And thank YOU who are reading this and pick up trash when you can, because each piece is important. Today, we picked 110 kg of trash within 2 hours! It’s really sad, but also empowering that we can make a change if we work together.
.
.
.
#strandryddedagen #strandryddeuka #beachcleanup #pickupyourtrash #plukkenpose #pickabag #lesswaste #lowwaste #noplastic

caption:
Another successful beach cleanup in Santa Monica this morning🤩 We collectively picked up so much trash and did our part to make a difference and I am soso grateful. Everyday I think about how scientists predict that by the year 2050 there will be more plastic in the ocean than fish. It’s terrifying but that thought alone is what keeps me motivated to clean up the beach and be an instrument for change.  Thank you again to all the volunteers and everyone that supports this and supports me. Thank you times a million.💫🌊 Special s/o to @viclitlikebic for this photo and @agarellano_ @dannyboyy48 for helping me set up!! 🌱🌱🌱 .
.
.

An easy start: use reusable water bottles (use @findtap to find water!), buy a bamboo tooth brush, take your own bags anywhere you go. And together, we'll help the world, bit by bit

caption:
@gretathunberg recently addressed the UK parliament, saying ‘I know many of you don’t want to listen to us – you say we are just children. But we’re only repeating the message of the united climate science.’⁣
⁣
She pointed out the UK shale gas fracking industry, the expansion of North Sea oil and gas fields, the building of more airports and planning permission of a brand new coal mine as ‘absurd’, as well as the UKs ‘creative’ carbon accounting. ⁣
⁣
We are not doing enough, we talk about climate change seriously, but this is not reflected in our actions.⁣
⁣
The greenhouse gas emissions curve is still increasing. Greta says that every time we make a decision, we should think about how it will affect the curve. Indeed, she says we should ask ourselves ‘have we got the carbon budget to spare to go through with this?’⁣
⁣
We know climate change is a real and dangerous problem. This is a fact. We’ve known it for years. We know that we must reduce our dependency on fossil fuels and make the economy more circular. ⁣
⁣
We haven’t quite figured out all the solutions yet, and this is where political inertia stems from. As Greta says ‘we have to start treating the crisis like a crisis – and act even if we don’t have all of the solutions’.⁣
⁣
Stopping climate change will require a lot of thinking and change to our economies and governments. We don’t know the answer yet, but we will find a way. Anything we all put our mind to, we can achieve.⁣
⁣
Climate change is real, and an emergency, let’s treat it like one.⁣ #change #climatechange #climate ( #clipperrace #theraceofmylife #l4l #f4f #follow #plasticpollution #nostraws #atlanticocean #carribeansea #carribean #dominicanrepublic #savethewhales #beachcleaning #beachcleanup #cleanseas #ttop #turnthetide #turnthetideonplastic #seaturtles #killsanimals #savetheearth #savetheworld #savetheoceans #earth

caption:
Wow 😍♻️🌳🌍💚.
.
Today we were incredibly proud to be part of ‘The Great Pot Amnesty’ at Trevisker Garden Centre, near Padstow. Where, over the bank holiday weekend, we are encouraging everyone to bring in all of their old, unwanted plastic garden pots and seed trays for us to collect, and then send off with the Ocean Recovery Project, to be recycled! ♻️🌍.
.
We really can’t put into words how inspiring today was for all involved. The community spirit that was shown should leave you all as full as pride as I am this evening.
.
Firstly, we must say a HUGE thank you to @trevisker_garden_centre 🌳 Today would not have been possible without all the team up there, a true credit to the community.
.
Secondly to the team at the @oceanrecoveryproject @fathomsfree @odysseyinnovation @beachcaresw for providing this system, which is allowing for the collection of unwanted pots and seed trays and the consequent recycling of these materials ♻️.
.
And last but not least, to everyone that took the time to dive into your garden sheds and haul out all of those old pots. It’s fair to say that today, the first day of ‘The Great Pot Amnesty’, we are close to filling the entire ‘Lovely Orange Lorry’ that @oceanrecoveryproject have provided us! These pots would have continued to have collected dust and cobwebs, been sent to the incinerator, or perhaps even into landfill, if it weren’t for all your efforts today. Thank you!
.
The Great Pot Amnesty is continuing tomorrow at @trevisker_garden_centre near Padstow 10-4! We have made plenty more room for many many more of you to get hunting for all your old, unwanted, plastic garden pots and seed trays and bring them along to be recycled into Marine Kayaks and more...
.
#IAmABeachGuardian

caption:
Why should we care?
.
.
.
A lot of people I know just don't seem to care that we use resources faster than the Earth can replenish them. They don't care that we're unsustainable, that we're killing our home and the home of animals, that we're seeing extinction of animals, that our air and water is polluted, that we create so much waste
They don't care.
🌊
🌊
🌊
But I do, and I know I'm not alone. So take a moment and ask yourself "Why do I care about the environment?" And let it strengthen your resolve to making environmental change. 🐠
🐠
🐠
I care because I'd be ridiculous not to. This is our home, let's not burn it down recklessly.

caption:
On éduque tous nos enfants dans le but de leur assurer un avenir meilleur. Mais nos efforts seront vains si on ne s’intéresse pas à la base. Qu’advient-il d’un palace s’il est bâti sur un sol marécageux ? Notre planète est notre maison à tous, notre sol, notre plafond, notre source d’air et de nourriture. A quoi leur serviront les diplômes universitaires, les comptes en banque garnis ou la dernière Mini, s’ils doivent racler la terre pour manger, vivre cloîtrée parce que l’air est pollué ou s'entretuer pour trouver un toit dans le peu d’habitat terrestre qu’il restera ?

Je me rends compte que ma vie, mes passions, mes ambitions sont un grain de poussière dans l’énormité du monde. Le documentaire Netflix « Notre planète » (A NE MANQUER SOUS AUCUN PRETEXTE) nous montre à quel point nous sommes tous liés… si ces chaînes parfois invisibles qui nous unissent cèdent, le mécanisme s’enraie et la Planète devient dysfonctionnelle.

Je n’ai pas de solution miracle à proposer, je n’ai pas peur de dire que je n’en ai pas l’intelligence. On vit en société et dans toute bonne société je juge que chacun a son devoir à accomplir, son savoir à apporter. Et d’après moi, l’avenir de l’humanité devrait être une affaire d’état. Il serait temps que nos gouvernements cessent de faire les marmottes et s’occupent de ce qui compte vraiment : l’avenir de l’humanité. Ils en ont les moyens. S’ils s’attelaient à la tâche, embauchaient les personnes compétentes pour y remédier (ou du moins freiner notre chute vers la catastrophe) et réunissaient tous les médias afin que chaque émission, show, concert, série, publicité, téléréalité, salons littéraires, Chaîne Youtube et autres supportes influents diffusent clairement les attitudes à adopter, le dérèglement climatique et l’avenir de l’humanité deviendraient plus qu’une information noyée parmi des milliers.

En attendant un tel miracle  de la part des dirigeants, essayons d’adopter les bonnes attitudes. Pour nous ce sera nettoyage de plage à Villeneuve Loubet avec nos enfants. Voici la vidéo sur YouTube « Dahlia culture kids ». https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=iKV5CFKovy4
#nettoyagedeplage #beachcleanup #beachclean #cleanbeaches #

caption:
✴04/05/2019✴

E non è tanto il raccoglierli che mi disturba, quello ormai è un brutto “vizio”. È il differenziarli dopo la raccolta che mi urta!

Almeno avessero l’accortezza di buttarli già per categorie!😂😂😂 Bisogna educare certa gente a sporcare in modo “differenziato”. Avremmo la vita più facile noialtri! 😀😀😀
O avrebbero dovuto avere mia nonna in casa che appena finito di mangiare ti differenziava pure gli scarti nel piatto: questo per le galline, quest’altro per il gatto, l’etichetta della mela nell’indifferenziata, mi raccomando, sennò mi si affogano le galline!😀😀😀😀 Azione n° 2 #30ecodays : “Fai la differenzia”

Today we walked in the country (el campo) This is probably polytunnel plastic, that has blown in the wind, then been washed towards the sea in the natural water channels (las ramblas). The the Spanish sun has then dried out the soil & the plastic is now impacted & stuck fast. 😪😢😭

caption:
Beach cleanup day! No matter where you are in the world, on average you will find about one ton of garbage per kilometer of beach. 
We joined a sizable army of volunteers today in an effort to clean up one of our local sand banks. Some of the fishing nets were so deeply buried and entangled that we had to cut them in half before we could drag them back to the collection point, though most items were small enough that we could put them on our trailers.

All in all, we filled up two massive containers with a vast array of marine trash, from fishing nets to empty bottles of household products and car tires.
~

caption:
Pellicole di plastica, carta e alluminio usa e getta addio! 
La cooperativa sociale Sonda ha realizzato "Apepak" un composto da fibra di cotone olio di jojoba e cera d’api 🐝, che non inquina e può essere riutilizzato 100 volte per singolo foglio 🌱.
Apepak è fatto di cotone biologico o riciclato dagli avanzi dei laboratori tessili italiani ♻️. La cera d’api, la resina di pino e l’olio di jojoba sono forniti da apicoltori e aziende italiane. 
Utilizzare Apepak potrebbe far risparmiare 9 kmq di involucri di plastica all'anno.
°
°
Goodbye disposable plastic, paper and aluminum films!
The social cooperative Sonda has created "Apepak" a compound of cotton fiber jojoba oil and beeswax, which doesn't pollute and can be reused 100 times per single sheet.
Apepak is made of organic or recycled cotton from the leftovers of Italian textile laboratories. Beeswax, pine resin and jojoba oil are supplied by Italian beekeepers and companies.
Using Apepak could save 9 sq. Km of plastic wrappers per year.
°

caption:
Beach clean findings from Cuckmere Haven for day 4 of #36adaymay. 
This is another exercise from the Photographer's Playbook: Sara Cwynar's brief to find a collection of related objects and photograph them in different arrangements.

I used my beach clean findings from yesterday, and attempted a flat lay. This style of photography is alien to me: it's deliberate and considered, which I don't normally do. It was tricky to get the light right, keep my shadow out of the shot and the background clear of sand. It was easier than I thought to come up with 36 different configurations though, and I enjoyed the slow, methodical way of working. I'm pleased with the results.

There's a few of my favourite images here, and all 36 in the video.

caption:
Small pieces, small acts, big difference🌍🐳
.
Fra dagens ryddeaksjon er dette det som gjorde størst inntrykk. Så himla mange små biter av plast- over alt! Når man rydder naturen er det ofte lett å overse disse små delene, ikke minst mikroplasten og nanoplasten, men det er jo DET som faktisk er blantdet mest skadelige for livet i havet, fugler og andre dyr. .
Det tar tid, men det er verdt å bruke noen minutter ekstra på hvert sted for å plukke med seg de minste bitene. Og ref bilde 2, vi må slutte å hive q-tips i toalettet altså🙈
.
Utrolig kult å se så mange folk som ryddet strandsoner og hav i dag👏🏻
Heia alle dere som rydder og tusen takk til de som stilte opp på Moss Miljøfestivals ryddeaksjon - @gronneresammen 🙏🏻🐳 @holdnorgerent .
.
.
#beachcleanup #endplasticpollution #strandryddedagen

caption: Very successful beach clean up this morning! Tons of those mouthpieces from cigars bottle caps and STRAWS!! I SWEAR I PICKED UP AT LEAST 30 STRAWS in less than an hour! At 1st I was angry but the sound of the ocean and walking around kinda calmed my thoughts after that I just felt kinda sad. All this shit ends up in the ocean!  in the bellies of beautiful sea life, the area we cleaned is equivalent to a drop in a bucket! WTF are we doing to the planet? As the summer season approaches please be mindful of trash if you see some pick it up if you bring it with you, take it with you it's really not that hard! Thanks to @gisaveswhales for organizing todays cleanup! A definite "feel good" way to start my day!  Now off to @rookcoffee to get my caffeine on! 😜 have a great Saturday everyone! 😘🙏💚 #jerseygirl #yogitillidie #beachgirl #jerseyshoreyogi #beachcleanup #plasticeverywhere #dowhatyoucant #protectoursealife #onesmallchange #keepourbeachesclean #environment #yogaoffthemat #oneuseplastic #saynotostraws

Stop using plastic bags and straws. It seriously ends up on our beaches and in our oceans killing our wildlife. Just think. Please. Nyåpnet plast- og havrestaurant #Under. Livet som #foodie består av reiser til eksotiske steder for å spise... New York-Kristiansand på 1.klasse bare 6860 kilo CO2 —3,5 års karbonbudsjett.
·
Nyt et måltid i omgivelser med #marinforsøpling hvor #plastavfall skaper et magisk lys. Hvorfor ikke prøve den autentiske opplevelsen av #plastforurensing? ­—Som å blokkere fordøyelsessystemet til du dør av kvelning og sult.
·
På menyen:
Forrett av #plastsuppe med sneiper, et dryss av #havfruetårer og kunstgress. Hovedrett med nylontau på en seng av #plastpose, garnert med qtips eller sugerør, krydret med #mikroplast fra #fastfashion og bildekk. Serveres på tidsriktig polystyren med elegant engangsbestikk av stadig ny #jomfruplast. Akkompagnert av #flaskevann smaksatt med deilig hormonforstyrrende #BPA og #BPU. En herlig blanding av salte smaker og nydelige undertoner av #miljøgifter. Bon appetit!
·
Hvert år havner 8-12 tonn #plastavfall i havet. Nedbrytningen av dette kan ta opp mot 600 år. Det spåes å være mer #plastsøppel enn fisk i havet innen 2050. Så #holdnorgerent, #kildesorter, bli med på #strandryddedagen og #plogging!

caption:
In 2014, I made an outreach table at one of my favorite places in the #BahamaOutIslands to share information on the invisible issue of ocean plastic pollution. A core group of us had been working on researching and exposing the problem since the 90s. I'm encouraged to see that while there is much to be done, ocean plastic pollution has entered the global conversation as a top environmental concern. This summer we're developing strategies for Wildblusea based on lessons learned in piloting Blue Mind infused ocean conservation initiatives around the North Atlantic the past 5 years. All hands on deck!
-

caption:
Mangrove challenge - 90 minutes of clean up, 3 volunteers on one mangrove equipped with knives in 30°c yet it's just "moderately clean"

Mangroves act as a buffer between the sea and the land, it reduces the impact of waves but now they work double time and also stop the marine debris which gets entangled in their branches and choke their roots as they shoot above the ground which is slowly killing them. 
Mangroves are one of the important habitat for marine ecosystem and serve as breeding spots for many species which play an important part in the marine and coastal ecosystem.

But thanks to our recklessness they are struggling to thrive and are choking to death in a grave of orphan plastic.

caption:
Beachcombed objects.

Beachcombing or in Dutch ‘strandjutten’ exposition @kaapskil 
In the past, when people had little money, they did it out of necessity. The wood from the beach was free building material and fuel. Nowadays, not much wood is washes up anymore.. but there’s still lot’s to be found. The museum is completely filled with beach litter.

The amount and diversity of objects found are unimaginable. From diving suits to couples shoes, TVs, lighters, helmets and pacifiers. Whatever thing you can imagine, it’s there!

~

caption:
Before Mr Forest and I walked this beach a few days ago, I had never picked up trash on a beach, only on trails in forests, and a few desert spots in AZ.  I follow several people on instagram who clean up the beach where they live and also where they travel. I have seen pictures but never in real life, what they clean up.  I have to add, what they do is phenomenal work! 💪💕💯
There are plenty of people who care around this area and do beach cleans. 
2 shotgun wads so far.
I found a few dog poo bags, but nothing compared to what people are dumping in Colorado where I hike frequently.  And of course, plastic bits but not many. 
The sea breeze was very refreshing and the scenery was exceptional. 🌊🌞👒😎🕶️

caption:
.This is not a nice  video showing you lovely landscapes, beaches and other places! .Though I am not an activist or moralist, I had to film these little sequences  about my findings on the beach in Usedom (Baltic Sea) when doing my daily morning walks. .The beaches on the island Usedom are cleaned every morning with a lot of effort and enthousiasm. .I could see it personally  with my eyes every day during my stay. .
.The striking thing I found out is that most of the items I found are a mixture between products focussing on the "to-go-consumption" or on the "single use". And the question I put to myself was: if I was a fish in the ocean, could I be able to avoid it? No chance at all!  After all, I concluded to pick it up and to throw it in the rubbish containers placed on the beach. 
This is only a very little contribution, but even better than doing nothing!

I just found a flyer - it is called "The Usedom project: Beach clean up" on 17th of May 2019. It is the biggest project for sustainability organized by young people in Germany.
#beachcleanup
@das.usedom.projekt 🙏🙏🙏
Find more information under www.das-usedom-project.de/mitmacher-und-unterstützer

text: @colorsinthelens dear Sabine, what an inspiring reflection! Many, many  thanks. I agree that  the problem is very much linked to education. When you do not learn the basics  about how to protect the environment and how to deal with garbage at home or in public, you end up as a person without any responsibilty towards the environment!
@die_knipserin 👍🏻 That‘s it - and we can not expect everything from the school - too, but first it's up to the parents (but even if they did not learn it)
Das macht sprachlos und sehr traurig 😢 😞😯 und wütend! 😡🤬
this is so sad and at the same time frustrating 😫😥😪
SO LET'S ACT !!! let''s all pick up whatever garbage we meet on our way...... and teach the next generation to not throw garbage in the nature.... small steps forwards is better than no steps taken
@_.artistas._ it is very sad, but not hopeless. There are voluntary projects by NGOs whichxstarted a beach clean up...many thanks! 🙏🙏🙏
@cristina_gemaque_fotos thank you. It is not hopeless, as I just wanted to initiate a reflection on this very sensitive topic. Thank you! 🙏🍀
@chuckmet ...but not hopeless, I would say! It is already a good start when ecerybody is taking care for  ghe  garbage he is producing. Thank you very much! 🙏
@vuvivi_de sad, very sad, but not hopeless! Thank you very much!🙏

@skovballesunivers thank you very much for your solution-oriented answer. I totally agree with it. You can only change by  action or activity. In my story I posted a flyer focussing on this subject. 🙏🙏🙏
@rustymood_ many thanks!  I am 100% sure to say that it is not hopeless! 🍀
@die_knipserin Definitely not hopeless, never give up hope. Little efforts will make a big difference.

@patrick.dbr yes, indeed Patrick. But not hopeless as everybody can start to reflect on his own behaviour towards packaging to use, the own garbage we are producing every day...it is already a big step!  Many thanks! 🙏

@die_knipserin There's too much "let's sit down and talk about possible solutions" and too little action..... So whenever you walk the dog (even if you don't have one 😊) - bring a bag and collect  the garbage you find... it does make a difference. Think global, but acål
@skovballesunivers I was going to say Think global but act local.... and then my dog decided to help me writing 😊 He wants to go for his evening walk....
@d_gaertner da stimme ich Dir 100% zu! Wir können es nur ändern, wenn wir bei uns selbst anfangen und Vorbild für andere sind. Dankeschön! 🙏
@martictures17 vielen lieben Dank. Die Hoffnung auf Besserung stirbt zuletzt! 🙏
@skovballesunivers it is a you say: starting there where you are! Many thanks for your kind feedback! 🙏🙏🙏

@skovballesunivers that is exactly what I thought when I was waling on the beach. The first day, I did not have a bag for collecting it. The next days I brought one with me to collect. Unfortunately, I do not have a dog 🤗🤗🤗

@martictures17 ... es ist wirklich kein schöner Zustand, außer Frage. Nicht zu verharmlosen. Daher habe ich es ja auch gezeigt. Und die regionale Aktion vor Ort (s. heutige Story) ist eine gute Initiative. Danke Dir sehr.
We have so much waste coming to our shores that hurts the eyes!
Der Mensch füttert die Natur mit Gift und das Meer spuckt es aus...jedes gefundene Teil am Strand ist ein Stück Unachtsamkeit! Es ist schlimm...

@augenblickkunst vielen lieben Dank für Deine Zeilen. Ich stimme Dir voll zu! Wo fängt es an, wo hört es auf? Unachtsamkeit trifft es voll, um den Ursachen für dieses Dilemma nachzuspüren. Ich danke Dir sehr! 🙏🙏🙏

@stonefish_dr many thanks. Sounds horrible. Here it is not so dramatic, they are really cleaning it zmup every day. However, it can only be solved, when people change their own behavior by getting more conscious towards environment.

-
PULIZIA PADULE DI FUCECCHIO
20 FEBBRAIO 2019

FUCECCHIO. L’associazione Sea Shepherd, in collaborazione con gli Amici del Padule di Fucecchio, ha effettuato una grande raccolta di rifiuti in Padule, in località Ponte di Cavallaia, nel comune di Fucecchio. 
L’iniziativa, che ha coinvolto una ventina di volontari, ha consentito di raccogliere in maniera differenziata alcuni quintali di rifiuti (separando vetro, plastica, alluminio e varie tipologie di rifiuti speciali). Fra l’altro sono emersi un fusto contenente olio esausto, una bombola da ossigeno di uso medico, varie batterie, e un vecchio fucile che è stato sequestrato dai carabinieri.
-

Dropped by the beach today to watch the sunset, and as always I can’t help but stop and pick up rubbish.
On this particular trip I managed to find (the bucket is mine):
🌏 More than 22 cigarette butts which took me less than 5 minutes to pick up from a nearby picnic area. 🌏A P-Plate. 🌏 A piece of shoe I saved from the surf
🌏 Straws 🌿 It really hurts me to know that this is what is happening to our beautiful ocean. That it is being filled with plastics and litter like this 🌿

caption:
What an absolute beautiful beach.. swipe to see what we found.
As you may know, @metalnotmeat , and my little men and I do a beach bbq every week, (plant based of course!) and do a beach clean up for @take3forthesea.
We go to a different beach every week and we are always surprised by how much we find, even when the beach appears clean on the surface.
But Murray's Beach today just blew us all away. 
Cigarette butts, fishing line galore, bait bags, plastic bottles... All devastating for marine life. Left by lazy fishermen who fish from the rocks here.
I cannot understand how humans can come to such a beautiful place and leave their mess. What they leave pollutes the oceans, and kills the animals that call it home.
Please leave nothing but footprints, and @take3forthesea while you are there.
I think we took about 333 today! .
.
.

I reached out to a community of strangers, with no clue who would show or be interested, within a day my Facebook group for it had 70 people!! caption: During the course of our 6 hour day at the beach, we watched probably 40-50 people walk or kayak past giant rocks to see caves and a waterfall. Behind and inbetween those rocks was so much ocean rubbish. If everyone had picked up just two pieces of ocean trash I bet that section of the beach would be cleaned. We filled a bag today with old buoys, PET bottles, an old flip flop and random pieces of plastic with hardly any effort. Of course others came back empty handed. Let’s leave the beaches cleaner then when we arrived! #beachcleanup #takeithome #noplasticjapan #savetheoceans #whathavewedone #teachthechildren #saynotoplastic #japanislands #boragabeach #miyakojima

caption: Walked less than 100m and this is how much rubbish we picked up off the beach. Ruby’s crying perfectly sums up how depressing this is 😢 Some other people were at the beach and saw me picking up rubbish but they just kept walking. Why don’t more people care about this? People often say to me that reducing single use plastic to is good for “people like you”, meaning people who dive! But reducing waste is good for everyone! #reducewaste #reduceplastic #pickupyourtrash #bansingleuseplastic #strawssuck #dontbeasucker #carefortheocean #lovetheocean #lovethesea #protecttheocean #beachcleanup #justmeandmydog #oceanconservation

caption:
WANT TO SAVE THE PLANET 🌍 AND YOUR  TEETH 🦷?
.
A metal straw not only reduces plastic consumption but did you know drinking through a straw also protects your teeth and those delicate teeth 🦷 🦷 of your children .
.

Here are the 13 most acidic fruits.. Lemon Juice 🍋 
Limes 
Cranberry Juice 
Blue Plums 
Grapes 🍇 
Pomegranates 
Grapefruits 
Blueberries 
Pineapples 🍍 
Apples 🍏 
Peaches🍑 
Mangos🥭 
Oranges 🍊 .

What is dental erosion ?
As hard as tooth enamel is, the high acid content in many fruits and fruit juices can cause it to weaken and demineralize over time... The goods news is you don't have to give up fruit in order to prevent erosion. .

Here are a simple few tips to keep your teeth healthy while maintaining your vitamin C requirement: .

1.  Use a straw when drinking fruit juices. .

2. Rinse with water after eating fruit to dilute the acids in your mouth, and wait at least 30 minutes before brushing to give your enamel time to resettle. .

3. Keep your enamel strong by brushing with fluoridated toothpaste.. .
.

4. Eat cheese after your fruit. This raises the pH levels in your mouth and increases saliva production, which also helps neutralize acids. .
.

SCAREY FACT
In the UK almost a quarter (24.7%) of 5 year olds have tooth decay, so 1 in 4 children will have tooth decay when they start school - ACT NOW .

If you want to protect your teeth and those of your children invest in a family pack of metal straws. You can even take them with you everywhere as they come in a cotton travel pouch and with their own cleaning brush .. FREE UK 🇬🇧 POSTAGE - get your family pack here 👇🏼👇🏼
www.themetalstraw.co.uk
.

Norway has beautiful nature everywhere you look and I especially love #northernnorway ´s white sandy beaches, turquoise waters, and tall, majestic, snowy mountains. But truth is that also here, the ocean, beaches, rivers, and coastlines are getting trashed with plastic and waste created and caused by humans. I don't think we mean to cause harm, to cause pollution,  we are just following along with what is, "mindlessly" living in a broken system. With that said, good things are happening and action is taken because we are waking up to the issues. Today is the official #Strandryddedagen in Norway, a part of #Strandryddeuka (beach clean up week) Over 1000´s of volunteers join @holdnorgerent in Norway's biggest collective clean-up initiative, to clean up the beaches, lakes, rivers and even the bottom of the sea. This is an inspiring, important and proactive way to help heal the planet and let nature heal you - It might not seem like it helps, but it surely does when everybody gets together. If anything we gain more awareness around what kind of trash that is out there. We also create community and inspire each other. I personally had a lot of fun running around on the beaches and streams here in Lofoten collecting all kinds of weird trash and things. Find and join a cleanup near you by using this link https://holdnorgerent.no/ryddeportalen/⁣ or visit my partner in creativity @eplehusetno as they provide clean-up kits  at any of their service centers located all over Norway- use the link https://eplehuset.no/strandryddedagen⁣
⁣

caption:
Often our most beloved places become the dirtiest. Swipe to see just some of the saddening pictures of trash and plastic I found on the beach today. Hawaii’s beauty is slowly getting taken over by the mentality that “it’s just one wrapper.” If a thousand people say the same thing then that’s x1000 worth of trash going into the oceans. The video on the last slide shows chip bags and a battery left on a table only 5 ft from a trash can. It is our aina and our kuleana to keep it clean. I will be hosting a Beach Clean-Up on MAY 11TH at KUALOA BEACH, 7:30AM. We will have snacks, drinks, and all supplies will be provided. Come out and make it a great morning! Please share this and if you are interested feel free to dm me for more details.💙
#WeLoveTheEarth #BeachCleanup #Hawaii #Oahu #Kaneohe #KualoaRanch #KualoaBeach #Kualoa #KeepOurOceansClean #KeepOurAinaClean #KeepOurSeaLifeSave #AolePlastic

caption: So I know this post strays from my norm of pictures of Denver, but lately I have felt that I have been taking a whole lot more than I have been giving. Even more so not practicing what I have been preaching. So tonight I decided to take a little action and bring a bag and a garbage picker out on my walk with Denver. We walked a few km’s at Tsawwassen beach and it wasn’t long before the bag was full of non disposable materials. I know ocean pollution is no revelation to anyone, but growing up in Tsawwassen and spending summers at the family cabin in Point Roberts it was easy to see how much trash ended up on shore. Hopefully this becomes more of a routine, it’s not much, but every little bit helps! #tsawwassen #beachcleanup #balloonsblow

caption:
At this year’s cleanups, look for our fun new poster filled with all kinds of things to learn about plastics - like this one all about the life cycle of a plastic bottle! ♻️
•
We know single use plastics can become marine debris and what those effects normally are, but what about production effects?
•
Well, just in case you needed another reason to support #dontdrillnc, in order to satisfy the 31.2 BILLION gallons of bottled water purchased in 2006, 17 BILLION gallons of oil were required! #DidYouKnow that if you take a standard plastic water bottle, and fill it about an 1/8 full with crude oil, that’s a pretty good estimate of how much it took to produce the plastic bottle 🤢 yikes.
•
Now...onto #ClimateChange. To produce those 31.2 billion gallons worth of plastic bottles, 2.5 MILLION TONS of CO2 were released into the atmosphere during production 😳 This CO2 either depletes our protective ozone layer, is absorbed by trees (deforestation is causing us to not have enough to absorb it all 😭), OR is absorbed by the ocean. When this happens, ocean temperature rises, ocean acidification occurs, all kinds of crazy bad things happen that cause more frequent severe weather events, harm animals, etc etc etc doom and gloom ugh
•
Now...#WaterScarcity 💧 It’s a real problem for people, animals, and the environment as a whole. So it’s a HUGE bummer that one plastic water bottle requires 3x the amount of water to produce it - LAME 😒 •
These water bottles are then shipped all over the place, using more fuel, releasing more CO2 emissions...
•
FINALLY, we have that nice lil water bottle in our hands, we chug it in 5 minutes and then......that’s it! We pitch it in the trash 🗑 •
This lil water bottle ends up in a landfill or the ocean (let’s say there no recycling in this pseudo hypothetical land) where it takes 450 YEARS to decompose (at best). It never goes away. It continuously breaks down into smaller and smaller pieces, but still manages to be harmful to wildlife and humans at just about any size.
•
But they’re convenient and I was thirsty for 5 minutes 🤷🏽‍♀️
•
[continued in comment below ☺️]

text:
All single use plastic products have a similar life cycle so I think it’s safe to say it’s worth investing in sturdy, solid lovable reusable products to replace them! 💙💚🌎🌍🌏 •
Every little effort adds up - yo, WE GOT THIS 💪💙🌊🚮
Will you sign my petition to get Publix supermarket to stop offering single use plastic produce bags? Here is the link https://www.change.org/p/publix-super-markets-stop-offering-plastic-produce-bags
My jaw is on the floor 😅 I knew it took a lot but not that much!!

Right?! And this is in 2006 - single use plastic production has only grown since then! AND this is ONLY for plastic water bottles. Doesn’t include bags, packaging, straws, caps, cigarettes, etc etc etc - it is mind blowing 🤯
can you imagine the stats with plastic soda bottles in the equation? 😭
@shopaltwood I know, it hurts my soul 😭

caption:
The good news about biodegradable/compostable plastic is it is typically made from plants rather than petroleum. The bad news is you need a large industrial composting facility to create the ideal conditions in which to break down these types of plastics. In fact, some recycling facilities consider PLA (made from corn) a contaminant. 
Shifting to “better” plastic is less of a solution than shifting away from all plastic altogether. 
Think reusable, not disposable. (Photo via @plasticpollutes)

caption:
Please join Sea Shepherd Long Island Chapter-less Group on Sunday, May 19th at Jones Beach - Field 6 for a beach cleanup. 
Millions of pounds of garbage are dumped into the oceans every year threatening marine wildlife. Fish and other sea animals can ingest large pieces of plastic that clog their intestines, or they can become entangled in plastic and suffocate. This is your chance to help save lives and make a difference. 
We will meet by the concession stand tables and clean the beach from 12:00–2:00PM. Bags and gloves will be provided.

Don’t forget to dress accordingly.  Please wear a Sea Shepherd shirt if you have one.

We look forward to seeing you there.

For more information please email SeaShepherdLongIsland@gmail.com 
#SeaShepherdLongIsland #SSCS #SeaShepherdConservatonSociety #BeachCleanup #SaveOurOceans

caption:
I am so inspired by our beautiful beautiful beaches and it’s disheartening to see them so polluted. “With skyrocketing plastic production, low levels of recycling, and poor waste management, between 4 and 12 million metric tons of plastic enter the ocean each year—enough to cover every foot of coastline on the planet!” - Oceanic Society .

Let’s all do better about reducing our plastic consumption, cleaning up after ourselves, and educating future generations. Our planet is so beautiful and let’s keep it that way.

Come this new piece “Save our Sea” today and tomorrow at @neimanmarcushawaii along with more art by me and amazing artists @butterfly_aloha and @jennawelleinart . 30% of all sales this weekend will go to benefit local sustainable organizations @kokuahawaiifoundation @sustainablecoastlineshawaii and @hnltoollibrary. 🌎 Don’t live in Hawaii?...don’t worry you can still help out! I will also be donating 30% of my online sales this weekend (no promo code needed). Together we can make a difference and save our sea! 💙 Mahalo!

caption:
Cheers to this week's #FrontLineFridays feature group, Operation Rich Coast (@operationrichcoast). From small, local roots, this Costa Rican volunteer organization has expanded to found a National Cleanup Day and much more. Thank you for all that you do! More about this wonderful group below.
.
How It Started: Operation Rich Coast started in their local community, Quepos Village, doing small clean ups. The group now promotes and organizes cleanups throughout the country and have founded National Cleanup Day, which this year united more than 1,500 people in 45 different locations simultaneously throughout the country.
.
Where Are The Cleanups?: Operation Rich Coast’s platform promotes the initiatives of every type of cleanup, including urban areas, beaches, rivers, parks, and more.
.
Contact: Follow Operation Rich Coast on Instagram and Facebook to find weekly schedules and ambassador contact names.
.
.
.

caption:
This rapid decline of coral needs to be treated with the importance and urgency that it deserves. Corals are not only habitat to some of the greatest diversity of marine species and protect our coastlines but they also help US by assisting in carbon and nitrogen fixing, and along with other marine plants produce 70% of the earths oxygen!!
—❌PLASTIC❌ suffocates and blocks the sunlight of these corals AND  increases deadly diseases in coral causing them to die and bleach by 89%!! —Coral is so important to balance in marine life, and also in our lives! Reduce your plastic consumption and help clean up beaches and go snorkeling for straws and plastics (strawkling) to make a difference!! Another big thing you can do is use reef safe sunscreens because along with plastic, the other chemicals that are effecting corals are from things like our sunscreen when we go for a swim! 🌍🐬
-
-
-photo from: @karmagawa -
-

My #36adaymay exercise was depressingly easy today. I went to Cuckmere Haven and took a picture of every piece of rubbish I found. I got 36 photos in minutes. The photos are simple - I've arranged them into colour groups here. 
I should say, I actually kind of like beach cleaning. Yes, it's awful that it's there. But I like being outside, doing something useful.

I picked up all of the rubbish up (obvs) and will take some different pictures of them tomorrow... #beachcleanup #2minutebeachclean #plasticpollution #beachcombing #recycle #beachcleaning #cleanseas #beachclean #cuckmerehaven #sussex #eastsussex #olympus #olympusomd #olympuscreators #photographersplaybook

caption:
Welcome aboard! Thanks to @vectoryachtservices we are the proud loaners of a 7ft tender and 3.5hp Mercury outboard. This boat will be used not only as a #safety vessel, but of course as a way to get us to shore to conduct #marinedebris surveys on the West Coast of @vancouverisland and run cleanups on the East Coast. With a reinforced bottom for those rocky shores, and easily compatible design, we couldn’t have asked for a better addition to our trip! 
P.s You could be the proud owners of this set-up in July when we complete the trip, as it will be for sale, with lots of stories to tell!

It’s great to see companies like Vector Yacht Services taking the opportunity to #seizechange this Summer

ECO-MONTH: BIG CHARITY EVENTS 🔥
⠀
⠀⠀In May 2019 project #BecauseWeLiveHere will be partners with big charity events:
⠀
#EcoTaleProject by Anastasia Otkidach @otkidach
⠀
#ArtSurfBoards - charity auction during The World Surf League's 2019 Corona Bali Protected.
⠀
⠀⠀All funds raised will go to the following purposes:
⠀
1️⃣. The construction of a local station for plastic waste recycling, with the release of finished products.
⠀
2️⃣. Test the river autonomous filtration system to collect garbage in an automatic mode with its further transportation to the local plastic recycling station.
⠀
3️⃣. Assistance to the orphanage on the island of Sumba.

caption:
WE CAN BREAK THE ROUTINE. FOR SURE ♻️
⠀
⠀⠀We decided to create an ECO investment platform and mutual assistance in the implementation of ECO- developed projects. We really want to realize our ECO-goals, so in May 2019 we will be partners with big charity events:
⠀
#EcoTaleProject 📷🎞
⠀
⠀⠀Fashion photography exhibition from famous photographer Anastasia Otkidach @otkidach
⠀
⠀⠀This art shows how pollution can kill the fairytale of life. Anastasia demonstrates the worst and most critical ecological problems of our times through images of gorgeous and innocent mythical creatures. Through her fairytale works we see how we kill our nature with oil, animal cruelty, air pollution and other displays of human madness.
⠀
⠀⠀Photo Project is meant to shock people's consciousness, draw their attention to the unspeakable scale of the ecological issues through the fairy-tale we have long forgotten.
⠀
#ArtSurfBoards 🏄🏻
⠀
⠀⠀We are planning to collect old surfboards at the exhibition as a charitable contribution.
Artists of the island will paint and decorate them in various art styles for the next event - a charity auction #ArtSurfBoards.
⠀
⠀⠀The charity auction will take place during The World Surf League's 2019 Corona Bali Protected. And we’ll invite to #ArtSurfBoards WSL Cup participants.
⠀
⠀⠀🌎 Now we invite sponsors, investors, marketing and environmental specialists, artists and content creators, architects and engineers, volunteers, to develop these proposals in full process.
⠀
Let’s break the routine together! It will be hot Eco-month. For sure🤙
⠀
presentation by @devyatsot @ecoworldvibe

caption:
Hello from Save the Children India, Delhi Chapter!

Plastic as a material is not harmful. What is harmful is when we don’t dispose it in the correct way and it stays in the environment damaging lives.  The power to stop plastic litter in cities, oceans, rivers and waterways lies in our hands. 
United Way Mumbai with the support of Hindustan Unilever Limited (HUL) organized a beach clean-up drive under the “Plastic Banega Fantastic” campaign. The plastic waste collected during the campaign will be segregated and recycled by HUL to create products such as benches, boats, planters and spectacles and donated to needy people.

Save the Children India participated in the beach clean-up drive to reduce marine pollution at the ITO Chhat Ghat with around 60 volunteers.

caption:
Es mag nicht besonders auffällig sein, aber trotzdem ist es da: Mikroplastik. Plastikpartikel mit einer Größe unter 5mm. Das meiste Mikroplastik stammt tatsächlich nicht aus Kosmetik oder Putzmitteln (sog. primäres Mikroplastik), sondern aus größeren Plastikteilen, die sich aufgrund von Wind, Wasser, Witterung o.ä. in die kleineren Teile zersetzt haben. Genau deshalb ist es wichtig, dass wir den kompletten Plastikverbrauch zurückfahren. Nach einer Studie des Umweltbundesamtes landen 6 bis 10% der weltweiten Plastikproduktion im Meer. Das ist nicht nur problematisch, weil Plastikprodukte oft noch giftige Chemikalien, wie zum Beispiel BPA, die dann in die Umwelt gelangen, sondern auch, weil Tiere wie Fische oder Vögel die kleinen Plastikteile fälschlicherweise als Nahrung betrachten. Viele Tiere verenden durch das Plastik in ihrem Magen, das sie nicht ausscheiden können. Sie verhungern also mit gefülltem Magen. Das Plastik kann außerdem ihren Verdauungstrakt verletzen oder vergiften. Die Mikroplastikpartikel sind nämlich exzellente Träger für Umweltgifte, andere Schadstoffe, Krankheitserreger oder invasive Arten. Und im Endeffekt landet der ganze Müll dann bei uns auf dem Teller, wenn wir Fisch oder andere Meeresfrüchte essen.

Hier auf dem Bild kann man sehen, was ich so am Strand finde. Neben dem ganzen Bimsstein auch sehr viel Mikroplastik: von der Bügelperle bishin zu unzähligen Styroporkügelchen ist alles dabei. Und das Schlimmste: es sind so viele, dass es einfach unmöglich ist, alles wegzusammeln... Und was ist mit den Teilen, die so klein sind, dass ich sie nicht sehen kann?

#nachhaltigkeit#nachhaltig#plastik#müll#müllsammeln#beach#beachcleanup#cleanup#strand#fjord#norwegen#öko#plastic#microplastic#mikroplastik#trashtag#umweltschädlich#umwelt#umweltschutz#sustainable#sustainability#strandryddeuka

Hemos decidido mantener Facebook para los amigos que viven o visitan Terreros (España); mientras que Instagram puede ser el lugar donde podemos mantener actualizados a los amigos de todo el mundo. Por lo tanto, si ha enviado una solicitud de amistad de Facebook y no hemos aceptado, le pedimos disculpas.
Sofía y Pedro 🐾 🐾

Available here in 8KG net bags but we can do larger or regular loads of any size up to the truck load. If you are visiting the Gower camping or holidaycottage and need firewood please let us know and we can arrange deliver or easy collection options for you. If you need wood for a party or beach fire we can deliver. Please do not use any fence posts or damage the #gowerbeaches for firewood. Get in touch and we can bring as much wood as you need to the beach for you. Working with Team RICD2019 and Trash Hero @trashherokl to clean up Teluk Keme. We spent well over an hour in the hot sun to cleanup and we still couldn’t complete the beach cleanup. From 4pm until 6.30pm it took us to complete the mission. There was just far too much trash and I’ve never seen so much. The monsoon last year and the currents bring the trash from all over South China Sea directly this this bay. caption:
A little bit of rain couldn't stop these volunteers from keeping our communities clean and green!

In honor of Earth Day, we held our annual multi-town cleanup which included 19 beaches, parks, and playgrounds across Marblehead, Swampscott, Nahant, and Salem on Sunday, April 28. 
Our effort consisted of 224 volunteers, 123 of whom were under the age of 17.  Collectively these volunteers netted over 60 bags of trash and piles of debris. Among notable items: 2 golf clubs, 3 beach chairs, a traffic cone, 2 lobster traps, a car bumper, a rubber snake, a plastic steering wheel, 3 shoes, $2 in loose change, and 4 hypodermic needles.

@salemsoundcoastwatch shared their knowledge and leadership at Stramski and Philips beach, and respective Towns & Cities helped support our effort by supplying trash bags and gloves.

Following the cleanup, volunteers stopped by our office and enjoyed pizza from our friends at @livelongandpizza . 
Thank you to all the volunteers who joined us this year! We are grateful to have you as part of our Community of Doers!

#CommunityOfDoers #SPURgooddeeds #volunteer #communityservice #earthdayeveryday #beachcleanup #EarthDay

caption:
THE END IS NEAR!
.
ALL YEAR, it has been a real-time environmental catastrophe. The Great Barrier Reef, an unparalleled ecological treasure that supports all sorts of sea life and a range of human needs, not to mention a huge tourist economy, has seen the largest coral die-off ever recorded. If this were a rare event, separated by many years from the next big die-off, the reef would rebound. But in the age of climate change, scientists say this and other tragedies are frighteningly likely to be compounded.
.
Experts have been tracking the destruction for months, announcing their final conclusions Nov. 29, 2018. They found that across a long stretch of the northern end of the reef, an average of 67 percent of the coral died, according to aerial and diver observations. In these zones, the reef’s lively colors have been replaced by antiseptic white of “bleached” coral. Though weather events helped spare other areas this degree of destruction, the reef’s northern portions had been the most pristine.
.
In this case, the problem appears to have been water temperature, which was up to two degrees warmer than the normal summer peak. This threw off the delicate balance between the coral organisms and the algae that provide them sustenance. Natural variability may have played some role in raising the temperature — it was an El Niño year, which means the Pacific Ocean was hotter. But global warming probably set the scene. Australian scientists concluded that this year’s coral crisis was rendered far more likely because of climate-change-related ocean warmth. As the planet continues to warm, human influence will be more and more likely to interact with natural variation in dangerous ways. Among other things, that means all that dead coral may not have a chance to rebound.(Text taken from The Washington Post)
.
.
.
#10yearchallenge #climatechange #globalwarming #plasticpollution #savetheplanet #savetheocean #savetheenvironment #coralreefs

A significant part of the waste included PET bottles, Flip flops, Styrofoam plates and different sorts of single use plastics. This goes to demonstrate the seriousness of our frame of mind towards appropriate waste management and our lack of care for our oceans and environment. We have do better.

Bag 2: 28kg
Bag 3: 53kg
Bag 4: 58kg
Bag 5: 53kg

caption:
The 4Wild Group (led by @rspb_love_nature Shetland) cleaned 22 bags from the beaches around Gletness, Nesting. 
The majority of bruck was ropes and net alongside two huge floats filled with tiny polystyrene balls. One float had partially broken which made the coastline on one beach look like it had been snowing! The team intend to contact local seafood firms for collection of these two large floats to avoid any further pollution from them so we are hopeful this will be a good outcome. Other interesting finds included a sun-baked pipefish, lobster tags and a metal tin of chocolate flavoured body paint! 🙈

This was a more remote area so the group would like to thank the locals that organised bruck removal with a quad to take it to the collection point. Great work everyone! 💚

#dvru2019 #dunnachuckbruck

caption:
Da’s lekker wakker worden. Een groen treintje en dag 1 van de interiorhomeloop2019 en dan tik je bijna de 1K aan 🙌🏻 Dus goede morgen allemaal! Ik ga zo lekker bij jullie #binnenkijken want er zijn zo veel nieuwe accounts om te ontdekken.  Heb me opgegeven als vrijwilliger voor de beach clean up in Noordwijk georganiseerd door @novasol. Dus straks handjes uit de mouw en duimen dat het ochtend zonnetje blijft plakken hier aan het strand. Mocht je in de buurt van Noordwijk zijn en nog niets te doen hebben vandaag. Check de website van www.NLvoorelkaar.nl en meld je aan. Dit is de eerste keer dat ik vrijwilligers werk ga doen. Ben heel benieuwd!
Doen jullie ook wel eens #vrijwilligerswerk? Vertel me over je ervaring. Want dit groentje heeft nog een hoop bezwaren en vooroordelen om zich overheen te zetten. Terwijl er in de basis toch niets mooiers bestaat als je de mogelijkheid hebt om andere te helpen. 
Anyhoe.... wat je ook gaat doen vandaag. Doe het met een glimlach en maak er een mooie dag van! 
Liefs, Reina

#blauwekeuken #keukeninspiratie #bluekitchen #kitchendesign #steelkitchen #nlvoorelkaar #stalenkeuken #brickwall

caption:
PLASTIC STATION ♻️
⠀
⠀⠀Each bag or plastic cup that we take out of the water, the sand, or the river potentially means a rescued turtle or a bird. And at the same time, every plastic bag or plastic cup that we send to be recycled means some good and some profit. So one of our project is #PlasticStation (project PlasticBack.com)
⠀
1️⃣ PLASTIC STATION - local station for the plastic waste recycling, with the release of finished products (building blocks, materials for road construction, playgrounds, etc.)
⠀
⠀⠀Required amount #PlasticStation: $ 20,000
When: July 2019
⠀
⠀⠀And the best addition to Plastic Station will be another our project - #RiverFilter
⠀
2️⃣ RIVER FILTER - river  filtration (energy autonomous) system to collect garbage for its subsequent separation into organic and nonorganic. Nonorganic garbage will go to Plastic Station and organic waste will go to #PosKompos
⠀
3️⃣ POS KOMPOS - organic waste recycling station for the manufacture of fertilized soil.
⠀
⠀⠀Required amount of #PosKompos: $ 20,000
When: August 2019
⠀
⠀⠀Thus, all these 3 components together will allow to recycle ~ 100% of garbage that will be collected in neighbouring villages, caught from the river and (in the future) collected from all villagers.
⠀
⠀⠀First #PlasticStation designed by @bluemoloko studio and  intends to stay on the river bank at @BLAGO_Retreat_Village ( Indonesia / Bali / Gianyar ).
⠀

caption:
Aspiga Beach Clean Up Campaign to mark World Environment Day (5thJune)🌏
For every pair of Kenyan Sandals sold between 1st May - 31st July 2019 we pledge to clear a basket full of plastic from Malindi Beach, Kenya.
The avoidance of plastic is core to our brand ethics. We recycle as much waste as possible and are on a mission to be a zero plastic office.
Our range of eco-friendly products include bamboo cotton buds, Ecoffee cups and S’well drink bottles.
Through our production processes we try to avoid air freight whenever possible, minimising the company’s carbon footprint.
Our packaging is reviewed regularly as we strive to create as little waste possible when sending our goods.
.

caption:
Kommt und macht mit beim Beach-Cleanup am Tag des Meeres am 8. Juni. Wir treffen uns um 10 Uhr am Baggersee in Spöck und sammeln alles ein, was nicht ins Wasser oder an den Strand gehört. Solange der Vorrat reicht, könnt ihr gerne unsere Boards haben - ihr dürft aber auch gern mit eurem eigenen Board kommen.
Wir freuen uns auf euch!!!
*
Come and join the beach cleanup on the Day of the Sea on June 8th. We meet at 10 a.m. at the lake of Spöck and collect everything that does not belong in the water or on the beach. As long as supplies last, you can have our boards - but you are also welcome to come with your own board. We are looking forward to seeing you!!
*
*

@ulyssespaulsen in Santa Barbara I get grain bags from the brewery. They are strong and often made of recycled plastics and I use them over and over. Usually leave a stash of a couple at the surf shack at Rincon and one or two in my truck. Brewers end up with countless of such and are happy to give em away for usage instead of throwing them away. They are great for pick up
